# Project: FinanceApp User & Access Management

## Scenario

Your company is launching **FinanceApp**.

You need to onboard 4 employees:

| User  | Role      | Group   |
| ----- | --------- | ------- |
| john  | Developer | finance |
| alice | Developer | finance |
| mike  | QA Tester | finance |
| emma  | Support   | finance |

Your responsibilities:

* Create group
* Create users
* Set passwords
* Create project directories
* Create files
* Assign ownership
* Configure permissions
* Create links
* Search files
* Manage passwords
* Lock/Unlock users
* Backup project
* Delete users
* Delete groups
* Remove project

---

# Step 1: Create Finance Group

```bash
sudo groupadd finance
```

Verify:

```bash
getent group finance
```

---

# Step 2: Create Users  || if you are using the -m and -G then (-m for the force the linux to create a user using the working directory if we do not use then we can not provide the space to the stpre file and anything -G for the add the user in existing group 

```bash
sudo useradd -m -G finance john

sudo useradd -m -G finance alice

sudo useradd -m -G finance mike

sudo useradd -m -G finance emma
```

Verify:

```bash
id john
id alice
id mike
id emma
```

---

# Step 3: Set Passwords

```bash
sudo passwd john

sudo passwd alice

sudo passwd mike

sudo passwd emma
```

---

# Step 4: Create FinanceApp Directory Structure

```bash
sudo mkdir -p /financeapp
```

Create subdirectories:

```bash
sudo mkdir /financeapp/development

sudo mkdir /financeapp/testing

sudo mkdir /financeapp/support

sudo mkdir /financeapp/shared

sudo mkdir /financeapp/backups
```

Verify:

```bash
tree /financeapp
```

---

# Step 5: Assign Ownership

Development team:

```bash
sudo chown john:finance /financeapp/development
```

Testing team:

```bash
sudo chown mike:finance /financeapp/testing
```

Support team:

```bash
sudo chown emma:finance /financeapp/support
```

Verify:

```bash
ls -l /financeapp
```

---

# Step 6: Create Files

```bash
sudo touch /financeapp/development/app.py

sudo touch /financeapp/development/config.conf

sudo touch /financeapp/testing/test_cases.txt

sudo touch /financeapp/support/tickets.log

sudo touch /financeapp/shared/project_notes.txt
```

Verify:

```bash
find /financeapp
```

---

# Step 7: Add Data

```bash
echo "Finance Application Code" | sudo tee /financeapp/development/app.py

echo "Database Configuration" | sudo tee /financeapp/development/config.conf

echo "Login Test Case" | sudo tee /financeapp/testing/test_cases.txt

echo "Customer Ticket" | sudo tee /financeapp/support/tickets.log

echo "Project Notes" | sudo tee /financeapp/shared/project_notes.txt
```

---

# Step 8: Permission Management

```bash
sudo chmod 775 /financeapp/development

sudo chmod 775 /financeapp/testing

sudo chmod 775 /financeapp/support

sudo chmod 777 /financeapp/shared
```

Verify:

```bash
ls -ld /financeapp/*
```

---

# Step 9: File Permissions

```bash
sudo chmod 644 /financeapp/development/app.py

sudo chmod 600 /financeapp/development/config.conf

sudo chmod 644 /financeapp/testing/test_cases.txt

sudo chmod 640 /financeapp/support/tickets.log
```

Verify:

```bash
ls -lR /financeapp
```

---

# Step 10: Soft Link

```bash
ln -s /financeapp/development/config.conf \
/financeapp/shared/config_softlink
```

Verify:

```bash
ls -l /financeapp/shared
```

---

# Step 11: Hard Link

```bash
ln /financeapp/testing/test_cases.txt \
/financeapp/shared/testcase_hardlink
```

Verify:

```bash
ls -li /financeapp/testing/test_cases.txt \
/financeapp/shared/testcase_hardlink
```

---

# Step 12: grep Practice

```bash
grep Finance /financeapp/development/app.py
```

```bash
grep Login /financeapp/testing/test_cases.txt
```

```bash
grep Ticket /financeapp/support/tickets.log
```

---

# Step 13: find Practice

Find txt files:

```bash
find /financeapp -name "*.txt"
```

Find files owned by john:

```bash
find /financeapp -user john
```

Find files owned by mike:

```bash
find /financeapp -user mike
```

---

# Step 14: Password Expiry

```bash
sudo chage -M 30 john

sudo chage -M 30 alice

sudo chage -M 30 mike

sudo chage -M 30 emma
```

Check:

```bash
sudo chage -l john
```

---

# Step 15: Lock User

Suppose Alice is on leave.

```bash
sudo passwd -l alice
```

Verify:

```bash
sudo passwd -S alice
```

---

# Step 16: Unlock User

```bash
sudo passwd -u alice
```

---

# Step 17: Backup FinanceApp

```bash
sudo tar -czvf financeapp_backup.tar.gz /financeapp
```

Verify:

```bash
ls -lh financeapp_backup.tar.gz
```

---

# Step 18: Delete a File

```bash
rm /financeapp/shared/project_notes.txt
```

Verify:

```bash
ls /financeapp/shared
```

---

# Step 19: Delete a Directory

```bash
rm -r /financeapp/support
```

Verify:

```bash
ls /financeapp
```

---

# Step 20: Offboard User Mike

Lock account:

```bash
sudo passwd -l mike
```

Kill processes:

```bash
sudo pkill -u mike
```

Backup home:

```bash
sudo tar -czvf mike_backup.tar.gz /home/mike
```

Delete user:

```bash
sudo userdel -r mike
```

Verify:

```bash
id mike
```

---

# Step 21: Offboard User Emma

```bash
sudo passwd -l emma

sudo pkill -u emma

sudo tar -czvf emma_backup.tar.gz /home/emma

sudo userdel -r emma
```

---

# Step 22: Delete Finance Group

After all users are removed:

```bash
sudo groupdel finance
```

Verify:

```bash
getent group finance
```

---

# Step 23: Remove Entire Project

```bash
sudo rm -rf /financeapp
```

Verify:

```bash
ls /
```

This is a much more realistic Linux Admin lab because it covers **multiple users sharing one project**, ownership, permissions, onboarding, offboarding, backups, links, file management, and cleanup in one complete workflow.
